00:10:11,602 --> 00:10:17,764
De tittar på natursignalerna.

94
00:10:17,803 --> 00:10:20,044
Deras uppfattning beror på de primitiva grunderna för utforskning.

95
00:10:21,904 --> 00:10:26,086
ASDIC, förfärd av Royal Navy, är ett sätt för att utforska smörjda submariner.

96
00:10:26,475 --> 00:10:30,256
The equipment consists of a metal dome attached to the hull underneath the ship.

97
00:10:30,277 --> 00:10:32,138
Inside this dome is a quartz oscillator.

98
00:10:34,958 --> 00:10:37,700
The oscillator is connected to a control unit on the ship's bridge.

99
00:10:41,681 --> 00:10:45,942
In operation when the control wheel is moved it rotates the quartz oscillator beneath the hull.

100
00:10:48,743 --> 00:10:51,464
Sound waves are sent out at regular intervals from the oscillator.

101
00:10:59,240 --> 00:11:03,562
The operator uses these waves like a searchlight to sweep the water around the ship.

102
00:11:03,582 --> 00:11:08,004
Each step of this sweep covers a segment of 10 degrees and the effective range is 2500 yards.

103
00:11:08,024 --> 00:11:16,469
When the sound wave strikes a solid object it rebounds and is heard as an echo on the operators headphones.

104
00:11:19,649 --> 00:11:22,932
A trained operator knows from the type of echo whether he has found his quarry.

105
00:11:30,899 --> 00:11:36,061
To make an attack, the ASDIC operator holds the quarry in his beam and the range is found from the recorder.

106
00:11:36,081 --> 00:11:40,341
A stylus travels across a moving paper band and makes a mark each time the echo is received.

107
00:11:40,783 --> 00:11:45,744
The distance between ship and submarine is found by comparing this mark with the range scale at the top of the recorder.

108
00:11:48,705 --> 00:11:56,148
By this means, the ship can be brought directly above the submarine, whatever evasive action it may take, and an attack with depth charges is delivered.

109
00:12:12,582 --> 00:12:19,230
In the spring of 1946, HMS Eastbourne, equipped with ASDIC, was attached to the Clyde Herring fleet for a series of experiments.

110
00:12:19,730 --> 00:12:29,760
Dr. Hodgson of the fisheries laboratory was aware that during the war years, many ASDIC operators had reported echoes which they knew were not of submarines and suspected that they came from shoals of fish.

111
00:12:30,461 --> 00:12:32,844
